## 5.Explain in your own words how NAT and PAT help apps like Zomato or Flipkart serve millions of users with limited public IP addresses. Give two real-world scenarios where incorrect NAT/PAT setup could break connectivity for users.
=>NAT (Network Address Translation) and especially PAT (Port Address Translation / NAT Overload) solve the IPv4 address exhaustion problem. Internet Service Providers (ISPs) and large companies have a limited number of public IPv4 addresses. Private IPs (RFC 1918 ranges like 192.168.x.x, 10.x.x.x) are used internally.

Millions of users/devices behind corporate/home NAT routers share one or a few public IPs.
PAT uses port numbers (the :80, :443, etc. in URLs) to distinguish between different sessions. One public IP can support thousands of simultaneous connections because each connection gets a unique source port.

Real-world benefit for Zomato/Flipkart:
When you open the Zomato app, your phone uses a private IP (e.g., 192.168.1.45). Your home router performs PAT and maps your request to the ISP's public IP + a unique port. Zomato's server sees only the public IP. This allows millions of users to access the service using far fewer public IPs than users.
Two scenarios where incorrect NAT/PAT breaks connectivity:

Port exhaustion / Misconfigured overload: If PAT is configured without "overload" (or with a very small pool of public IPs), and too many users try to connect simultaneously, the router runs out of available ports. New connections fail (especially for apps using many WebSocket/persistent connections like live tracking on Zomato or Flipkart). Users see "connection timeout" or "server unreachable" while others on the same network work.
Static NAT instead of PAT for many devices, or missing "ip nat inside/outside": If an admin configures one-to-one static NAT for hundreds of internal servers/devices but only has a handful of public IPs, most devices lose internet access. Or if interfaces are not marked ip nat inside / ip nat outside, no translation happens → internal PCs cannot reach external servers (pings/web requests fail), even though routing works internally.
